* ''[[Cancer Ward]]'' (1968; [[novel]])
* ''[[The Love-Girl and the Innocent]]'' (1969; [[play (theatre)|play]]), a.k.a. ''The Prisoner and the Camp Hooker'' or ''The Tenderfoot and the Tart''.
* ''Nobel Prize [http://nobelprize.org/literature/laureates/1970/solzhenitsyn-lecture.html delivered speech] (1970)The speech was delivered to the [[Swedish Academy]] in writing and not actually given as a lecture.
* ''[[August 1914]]'' (1971). The beginning of a history of the birth of the USSR in an [[historical novel]]. The novel centers on the disastrous loss in the [[Battle of Tannenberg (1914)|Battle of Tannenberg]] in August 1914, and the ineptitude of the military leadership. Other works, similarly titled, follow the story: see [[The Red Wheel]] (overall title).
* ''[[The Gulag Archipelago]]'' (three volumes) (1973–1978), not a memoir, but a history of the entire process of developing and administering a [[police state]] in the Soviet Union.
* ''[[Prussian Nights]]'' (Finished in 1951, first published in 1974; poetry)
* ''Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn's [http://nobelprize.org/literature/laureates/1970/solzhenitsyn-speech74-e.html speech] at the Nobel Banquet at the City Hall in Stockholm, 10 December 1974
* Aleksandr Isaevich Solzhenitsyn, ''A Letter to the Soviet leaders'', Collins: Harvill Press (1974), ISBN 0-06-013913-7
* ''[[The Oak and the Calf]]'' (1975)
* ''Lenin in Zürich'' (1976; separate publication of chapters on [[Lenin]], none of them published before this point, from ''[[The Red Wheel]]''. They were later incorporated into the 1984 edition of the expanded ''August 1914''.)
* ''Warning to the West'' (1976; 5 speeches (translated to English), 3 to the Americans in 1975 and 2 to the British in 1976)
* ''Harvard Commencement Address (1978) [http://www.columbia.edu/cu/augustine/arch/solzhenitsyn/harvard1978.html link]
* ''The Mortal Danger: Misconceptions about Soviet Russia and the Threat to America'' (1980)
* ''Pluralists'' (1983; political pamphlet)
* ''November 1916'' (1983; novel in ''[[The Red Wheel]]'' sequence)
* ''Victory Celebration'' (1983)
* ''Prisoners'' (1983)
* ''Godlessness, the First Step to the Gulag. Templeton Prize Address, London, 10 May'' (1983)
* ''[[August 1914]]'' (1984; novel, much-expanded edition)
* ''Rebuilding Russia'' (1990)
* ''March 1917'' (1990)
* ''April 1917''
* ''The Russian Question'' (1995)
* ''{{cite book |title=Invisible Allies |last=Solzhenitsyn |first=Aleksandr |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1997 |publisher=Basic Books |location= |isbn=978-1-887178-42-6 |pages=|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5yYBZ35HPo4C&amp;dq}}
* ''Russia under Avalanche'' (''Россия в обвале'',1998; political pamphlet) (Complete text in Russian:&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Title Unknown &lt;!-- BOT GENERATED TITLE --&gt;|url=http://www.geocities.com/solzh/Solzh/v_obvale_toc.html|work=|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kmWS9S0F|archivedate=25 October 2009|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;)
* ''[[Two Hundred Years Together]]'' (2003) on Russian-Jewish relations since 1772, aroused ambiguous public response.&lt;ref name=guardian&gt;{{cite news | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2003/jan/25/russia.books | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Solzhenitsyn breaks last taboo of the revolution | date=25 January 2003}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/news/article/20010723RussianJewsaccuse.html]{{Dead link|date=December 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.orthodoxytoday.org/articles/ChukovskayaSolzhenitsyn.htm Interview with Solzhenitsyn about &quot;200 Years Together&quot;] Lydia Chukovskaya, OrthodoxyToday.com 1–7 January 2003.&lt;/ref&gt;

