Aquaculture is an especially important economic activity in China. Between 1980 and 1997, the Chinese Bureau of Fisheries reports, aquaculture harvests grew at an annual rate of 16.7 percent, jumping from {{convert|1900000|t}} to nearly {{convert|23000000|t}}. In 2005, China accounted for 70% of world production.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/12.05/fish.html Wired 12.05: The Bluewater Revolution]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A31159-2005Jan23 | work=The Washington Post | title=Fish Farming's Bounty Isn't Without Barbs | first=Juliet | last=Eilperin | date=2005-01-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aquaculture is also currently one of the fastest growing areas of food production in the U.S.&lt;ref name=&quot;providence1&quot;/&gt;

[[File:Fish farming in High Island, Hong Kong.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mariculture]] off [[High Island, Hong Kong|High Island]], [[Hong Kong]]]]

